---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Take action"
  description="Plain steps to file an FCC informal complaint, link out to your state attorney general, and per carrier dispute pages."
>
  <div class="wrap prose" data-pagefind-body>
    <h1>Take action</h1>

    <div class="notice">
      <p>
        This hub gives general information, not legal advice. Using it does not
        make us your lawyer, and no outcome is guaranteed. Read the full
        <a href="/legal/action-hub-disclaimer">action hub disclaimer</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      The most important rule on this page: use your own words. Tell what
      actually happened to you. Do not copy anyone else's complaint. Regulators
      discount copy and paste floods, and identical text reads as a script. Your
      own honest account is what carries weight.
    </p>

    <h2>File an FCC informal complaint</h2>
    <p>
      The FCC takes informal complaints from consumers about phone and billing
      issues. It is free and you do it yourself.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Go to the FCC consumer complaint center at
        <a
          href="https://consumercomplaints.fcc.gov"
          rel="nofollow noopener"
          target="_blank">consumercomplaints.fcc.gov</a
        >.
      </li>
      <li>Pick the phone category, then the billing issue that fits.</li>
      <li>
        Enter your carrier and your own account details. You are describing your
        own situation.
      </li>
      <li>
        In the description, write what happened in your own words. Include
        dates, what you were promised, and what actually happened.
      </li>
      <li>Submit. Keep a copy of your confirmation.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="hint">
      An informal complaint does not guarantee any result. It puts your account
      on the record with the agency.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact your state attorney general</h2>
    <p>
      Every state has an attorney general office that takes consumer complaints.
      This is a separate path from the FCC and it is worth doing.
    </p>
    <p>
      We do not link one state here, because yours is the one that matters.
      Search for your state name and "attorney general consumer complaint." Use
      the official state government site, the one ending in your state's
      official domain. File there with your own facts.
    </p>
    <p class="hint">
      We point you to the official state channel and let you choose it, so you
      always land on the real government form, not a look alike.
    </p>

    <h2>Dispute with your carrier</h2>
    <p>
      You can also raise a dispute directly with your carrier. We keep a page
      per carrier with what we can verify.
    </p>
    <ul class="card-grid">
      <li class="card">
        <h3>AT&T</h3>
        <p>Dispute channel details.</p>
        <a class="btn secondary" href="/take-action/att">AT&T dispute page</a>
      </li>
      <li class="card">
        <h3>Verizon</h3>
        <p>Dispute channel details.</p>
        <a class="btn secondary" href="/take-action/verizon"
          >Verizon dispute page</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="card">
        <h3>T-Mobile</h3>
        <p>Dispute channel details.</p>
        <a class="btn secondary" href="/take-action/tmobile"
          >T-Mobile dispute page</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Tell your story</h2>
    <p>
      Sharing your story here helps show a pattern. It is separate from filing a
      complaint. <a href="/tell">Tell your story</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
